\q2
\v 6 \w then|strong="G1161"\w* \w Jesse|strong="G2421"\w* begot \w David|strong="G1138"\w* \w the|strong="G1537"\w* \w king|strong="G3588"\w*. \w Then|strong="G1161"\w* \w King|strong="G3588"\w* \w David|strong="G1138"\w* begot \w Solomon|strong="G4672"\w* \w by|strong="G1537"\w* \w her|strong="G3588"\w* \it who was\it* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Uriah|strong="G3774"\w*,\f + \fr 1:6 \ft Sins may be forgiven, but your curriculum remains—3,000 years later we still read about David's sin (Bathsheba is not named, she was Uriah's wife). The only women included in the genealogy (Tamar, Rahab, Ruth [Deuteronomy 23:13], Bathsheba) represent some violation—perhaps to emphasize the grace of God.\f*   
\q1
\v 7 \w then|strong="G1161"\w* \w Solomon|strong="G4672"\w* begot \w Rehoboam|strong="G4497"\w*, \w then|strong="G1161"\w* \w Rehoboam|strong="G4497"\w* begot Abijah, \w then|strong="G1161"\w* Abijah begot Asa;   
