\v 13 \w Therefore|strong="G1223"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w speak|strong="G2980"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G1722"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w parables|strong="G3850"\w*, \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w seeing|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* see \w and|strong="G2532"\w* hearing \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* hear \w nor|strong="G3761"\w* \w understand|strong="G4920"\w*.\f + \fr 13:13 \ft This is in response to \+nd their\+nd* choice, as verses 14-15 make clear. But Jesus only started using parables after the Pharisees blasphemed the Holy Spirit—they formally rejected Jesus as Messiah. Notice that the declared purpose of the parables is that the people \+nd not\+nd* understand. It follows that doctrine should never be based on a parable, unless Jesus interprets it—the interpretation may be used, but not the parable itself.\f*  
