\v 32 \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w indeed|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w smaller|strong="G3398"\w* \w than|strong="G3173"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w seeds|strong="G4690"\w*,\f + \fr 13:32 \ft That is, seeds normally planted in gardens.\f* \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w when|strong="G3752"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w grown|strong="G3173"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w greater|strong="G3173"\w* \w than|strong="G3173"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w vegetables|strong="G3001"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w becomes|strong="G1096"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w tree|strong="G1186"\w*, \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w birds|strong="G4071"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w air|strong="G3772"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w rest|strong="G2681"\w*\f + \fr 13:32 \ft The verb I have rendered ‘to rest’ is a compound form. The noun root refers to a temporary shelter, like a tent or a hut. The verbal form means to make use of such a shelter. Here the preposition κατα is prefixed to the verb, emphasizing, as I suppose, the temporariness. In Mark 4:32 the Text says that the birds can use the \+nd shade\+nd*, not the branches. But shade moves with the sun, and with the wind—how can you build a nest in something that keeps moving around (the Text actually says ‘under its shade’)?\f* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w its|strong="G3956"\w* \w branches|strong="G2798"\w*.”   
