\v 51 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w cut|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G2532"\w* two \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w appoint|strong="G5087"\w* \w his|strong="G2532"\w* \w portion|strong="G3313"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w hypocrites|strong="G5273"\w*.\f + \fr 24:51 \ft Notice that the Lord consigns hypocrites to hell. That servant pretended to be faithful while the owner was around, but as soon as he turned his back…\f* \nd \+w There|strong="G1563"\+w*\nd*, \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w weeping|strong="G2805"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w gnashing|strong="G1030"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w teeth|strong="G3599"\w*.\f + \fr 24:51 \ft This is a \+nd servant\+nd* who had gained his master's confidence, but then betrayed it—he winds up in hell. He was director of food services, and if he had been faithful there he would have been promoted to general director (verse 47), but…\f*   
\c 25  
\s1 Parable of the ten virgins  
\m
\v 1 “\w Then|strong="G5119"\w*\f + \fr 25:1 \ft “Then”—this temporal adverb links the parable to the prior context, which is dealing with the Rapture (I think). Since the foolish ones are virgins, not prostitutes, and since they also had some oil (does the oil represent the Holy Spirit?), this parable may point to a partial rapture; only those who are ready are taken.\f* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* kingdom \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w heavens|strong="G3772"\w* \w will|strong="G3748"\w* \w be|strong="G1519"\w* \w like|strong="G3666"\w* \w ten|strong="G1176"\w* \w virgins|strong="G3933"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w*, \w taking|strong="G2983"\w* \w their|strong="G1438"\w* \w lamps|strong="G2985"\w*, \w went|strong="G1831"\w* \w out|strong="G1831"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w meet|strong="G5222"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w bridegroom|strong="G3566"\w*.  
