\v 46 \w And|strong="G1161"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w ninth|strong="G1766"\w* \w hour|strong="G5610"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w cried|strong="G5610"\w* \w out|strong="G5456"\w* \w with|strong="G2316"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* \nd \+w loud|strong="G3173"\+w*\nd* \w voice|strong="G5456"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*, “\it Eli, Eli, lima sabachtani\it*?” \w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w means|strong="G1510"\w*, “\w My|strong="G1473"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w why|strong="G2444"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* \w You|strong="G3004"\w* \w abandoned|strong="G1459"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*?”\f + \fr 27:46 \ft I take it that the Father turned His back on the Son during those three hours—to be separated from the Father is spiritual death. For Jesus to pay for my sin and yours He had to take our wages: “The wages of sin is death”—both physical and spiritual.\f*  
\v 47 \w So|strong="G1161"\w* \w upon|strong="G3588"\w* hearing \w it|strong="G3754"\w* \w some|strong="G5100"\w* \w of|strong="G5100"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w bystanders|strong="G2476"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w This|strong="G3778"\w* \it man\it* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w calling|strong="G5455"\w* \w Elijah|strong="G2243"\w*.”  
\v 48 Right \w then|strong="G2532"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w them|strong="G2532"\w* \w ran|strong="G5143"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w took|strong="G2983"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w sponge|strong="G4699"\w*, \w filled|strong="G4130"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w with|strong="G1537"\w* \w sour|strong="G3690"\w* \w wine|strong="G3690"\w*, \w put|strong="G4060"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w on|strong="G1537"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w reed|strong="G2563"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* started \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w give|strong="G4222"\w* \w Him|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w drink|strong="G4222"\w*;  
\v 49 \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w rest|strong="G3062"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*: “Don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w*! \w Let|strong="G1161"\w*'s \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w Elijah|strong="G2243"\w* \w comes|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w save|strong="G4982"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.”\f + \fr 27:49 \ft Comparing this verse with Mark 15:36 we have an apparent discrepancy: Matthew records that others told the man to stop, while Mark records that the man told them to stop! So which is it? What I imagine is this: as both accounts state, a certain man [could it possibly have been John Mark himself?] decides to offer Jesus a drink of wine vinegar; several others, supposing that Jesus had just called on Elijah, tell him to stop; to which he retorts, “You (pl) stop!” and repeats their statement with sarcasm [anyone who really understood the language would have known that Jesus wasn't calling Elijah at all]. However, it does appear that the man stopped his action before Jesus could drink, since a bit later Jesus says, “I'm thirsty” (John 19:28).\f*   
\s1 The shout of \bdit victory\bdit*  
\p
\v 50 \w Then|strong="G1161"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w called|strong="G3588"\w* \w out|strong="G2896"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w* \w with|strong="G4151"\w* \w a|strong="G1161"\w* \w great|strong="G3173"\w* \w shout|strong="G2896"\w* \w and|strong="G1161"\w* dismissed \w His|strong="G3588"\w* \w spirit|strong="G4151"\w*.\f + \fr 27:50 \ft Oh praise God! Jesus dismissed His spirit (see also John 19:30)—it was not the cross that killed Him (for details see the note at 27:54 below). As He said in John 10:18, “no one takes it from me, but I lay it down of myself”. I take it that John 19:30 gives the content of the shout—\+it Τετελεσται!\+it* = “Paid in full!” It was a shout of victory.\f*  
\v 51 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \nd \+w then|strong="G2532"\+w*\nd*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w veil|strong="G2665"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w temple|strong="G3485"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* ripped \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* top \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w bottom|strong="G2736"\w*!\f + \fr 27:51 \ft God Himself ripped the veil (or ordered it done). Access to God's presence is no longer limited to one man once a year. See Hebrews 10:19-22.\f* \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w earth|strong="G1093"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w shaken|strong="G4579"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w rocks|strong="G4073"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w split|strong="G4977"\w*,  
\v 52 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w graves|strong="G3419"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* opened. (\w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w many|strong="G4183"\w* \w bodies|strong="G4983"\w*, \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* saints \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w fallen|strong="G2837"\w* \w asleep|strong="G2837"\w*, \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w raised|strong="G1453"\w*;  
\v 53 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w coming|strong="G1831"\w* \w forth|strong="G1831"\w* \w out|strong="G1831"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w graves|strong="G3419"\w* \nd \+w after|strong="G3326"\+w*\nd* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w resurrection|strong="G1454"\w*, \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w entered|strong="G1525"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* holy \w city|strong="G4172"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w made|strong="G1519"\w* visible \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w many|strong="G4183"\w*.\f + \fr 27:53 \ft Wow! How would you like a departed saint to knock at your door?! It would be tremendous confirmatory evidence for Christ's resurrection. The Text does not say what happened to these resurrected saints, but to be sent back into the ground would be a real drag. It is more likely that they went with the risen Christ to heaven.\f*)  
\v 54 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w when|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w centurion|strong="G1543"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* guarding \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w earthquake|strong="G4578"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w all|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w happened|strong="G1096"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* scared stiff \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w This|strong="G3778"\w* \it Man\it* really \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*!”\f + \fr 27:54 \ft “All that happened” is better explained in Mark 15:39—the loud shout followed immediately by death convinced the centurion. He had seen many crucifixions and was doubtless hardened to it. He knew that a person on a cross dies from asphyxiation. The weight of the body pushes the diaphragm against the lungs and you cannot breathe. Nailing the feet was a sadistic procedure that prolonged the agony—rather than die they would push against the nail to get a breath. Finally, when too weak to do that they would die for lack of air. (That is why they broke the legs of the two thieves; they then died within a few minutes.) Obviously, if you are dying without air you cannot shout! The centurion knew that the cross had not killed Jesus. But what mere human can just tell his spirit to leave? 2 + 2 = 4. Jesus had to be the Son of God.\f*   
\p
\v 55 \w Many|strong="G4183"\w* \w women|strong="G1135"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* followed \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w from|strong="G3588"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*, \w ministering|strong="G1247"\w* \w to|strong="G1161"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w also|strong="G1161"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w looking|strong="G2334"\w* \w on|strong="G1161"\w* \w from|strong="G3588"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* \w distance|strong="G3113"\w*;\f + \fr 27:55 \ft “Ministering to Him”—here we may have a clue as to how Jesus was maintained financially during His ministry, since He presumably did not have time for carpentry.\f*  
\v 56 \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w Mary|strong="G3137"\w* \w Magdalene|strong="G3094"\w*, \w Mary|strong="G3137"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w mother|strong="G3384"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w James|strong="G2385"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* Joses, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w mother|strong="G3384"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w sons|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Zebedee|strong="G2199"\w*.   
\s1 The burial  
\p
\v 57 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w at|strong="G1161"\w* \w evening|strong="G3798"\w* \w there|strong="G2532"\w* \w appeared|strong="G1096"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w rich|strong="G4145"\w* \w man|strong="G4145"\w* \w from|strong="G2064"\w* Arimathea, \w named|strong="G5122"\w* \w Joseph|strong="G2501"\w*, \w who|strong="G3739"\w* himself \w had|strong="G2424"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w become|strong="G1096"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w disciple|strong="G3100"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*.\f + \fr 27:57 \ft He “appeared”—he had been waiting in the wings. Just as with the owner of the donkey, and the owner of the upper room, who were doubtless advised in advance that their services would be needed, Joseph was prepared. He didn't just “happen” to have a tomb he didn't know what to do with, complete with a large stone just right for sealing. According to Isaiah 53:9 He was to have a rich man's grave, not whatever the common criminals got (the Father did not allow the Son's body to suffer that humiliation).\f*  
\v 58 \w This|strong="G3778"\w* \w man|strong="G3778"\w* \w went|strong="G4334"\w* \w to|strong="G4334"\w* \w Pilate|strong="G4091"\w* \w and|strong="G4334"\w* asked \w for|strong="G3778"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w body|strong="G4983"\w* \w of|strong="G4983"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*. \w Then|strong="G5119"\w* \w Pilate|strong="G4091"\w* \w ordered|strong="G2753"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w body|strong="G4983"\w* \w be|strong="G3588"\w* given.  
\v 59 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w taking|strong="G2983"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w body|strong="G4983"\w* \w Joseph|strong="G2501"\w* \w wrapped|strong="G1794"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w clean|strong="G2513"\w* \w linen|strong="G4616"\w* \w cloth|strong="G4616"\w*  
\v 60 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w placed|strong="G5087"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w his|strong="G1722"\w* \it own\it* \w new|strong="G2537"\w* \w tomb|strong="G3419"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w cut|strong="G2532"\w* \w out|strong="G2532"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w rock|strong="G4073"\w*. \w Then|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w rolled|strong="G4351"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w large|strong="G3173"\w* \w stone|strong="G3037"\w* \w against|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w door|strong="G2374"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w tomb|strong="G3419"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* left.  
\v 61 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w Mary|strong="G3137"\w* \w Magdalene|strong="G3094"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w other|strong="G1161"\w* \w Mary|strong="G3137"\w*, \w sitting|strong="G2521"\w* opposite \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w grave|strong="G5028"\w*.   
\s1 The tomb is guarded  
\p
\v 62 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w next|strong="G1887"\w* \w day|strong="G1887"\w*, \w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w after|strong="G3326"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Preparation|strong="G3904"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w chief|strong="G2532"\w* priests \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Pharisees|strong="G5330"\w* \w went|strong="G2532"\w* \w together|strong="G4863"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w Pilate|strong="G4091"\w*  
\v 63 \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w Sir|strong="G2962"\w*, \w we|strong="G3754"\w* \w remember|strong="G3403"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w deceiver|strong="G4108"\w*, \w while|strong="G2250"\w* \w still|strong="G2089"\w* \w alive|strong="G2198"\w*, \w said|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w After|strong="G3326"\w* \w three|strong="G5140"\w* \w days|strong="G2250"\w* \w I|strong="G3754"\w* \w am|strong="G3588"\w* going \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w rise|strong="G1453"\w*.’  
\v 64 \w Therefore|strong="G3767"\w* \w command|strong="G3004"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w grave|strong="G5028"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w made|strong="G4413"\w* secure \w until|strong="G2193"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w third|strong="G5154"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*, \w lest|strong="G3379"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w come|strong="G2064"\w* \w by|strong="G2532"\w* night \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w steal|strong="G2813"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w people|strong="G2992"\w*, ‘\w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w raised|strong="G1453"\w* \w from|strong="G2064"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w dead|strong="G3498"\w*,’ \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w last|strong="G2078"\w* \w deception|strong="G4106"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w worse|strong="G5501"\w* \w than|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w first|strong="G4413"\w*.”  
\v 65 \w So|strong="G5613"\w* \w Pilate|strong="G4091"\w* \w said|strong="G5346"\w* \w to|strong="G2192"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w You|strong="G5613"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w guard|strong="G2892"\w*; \w go|strong="G5217"\w* make \w it|strong="G5613"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* secure \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w you|strong="G5613"\w* \w can|strong="G1492"\w*!”\f + \fr 27:65 \ft Was Pilate happy? No he was not! And maybe, just maybe, he was not as stupid as some might like to think. From Mark 15:44-45 we know that he debriefed the centurion, who had to explain why Jesus died sooner than expected! “Make it as sure as you can.” Right. For a detailed analysis concerning Pilate, please see the Appendix: Poor Pilate—wrong place, wrong time.\f*  
\v 66 \w So|strong="G1161"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w went|strong="G4198"\w* \w and|strong="G1161"\w* secured \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w grave|strong="G5028"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w guard|strong="G2892"\w*, having \w sealed|strong="G4972"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w stone|strong="G3037"\w*.\f + \fr 27:66 \ft Ironically those great champions of the Sabbath had to violate the Sabbath to secure the tomb. They thought they were being shrewd, but only played into God's hand. Their effort only made the evidence for the resurrection all the stronger.\f*   
\c 28  
\ms1 Resurrection Day—Sunday, 04/07/30  
\m
\v 1 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w after|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Sabbath|strong="G4521"\w*, \w at|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* dawning \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w first|strong="G1520"\w* \w day|strong="G4521"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w week|strong="G4521"\w*, \w Mary|strong="G3137"\w* \w Magdalene|strong="G3094"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w other|strong="G1161"\w* \w Mary|strong="G3137"\w*, \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w see|strong="G2334"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* tomb.  
\v 2 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w then|strong="G2532"\w*, \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w big|strong="G3173"\w* \w earthquake|strong="G4578"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w occurred|strong="G1096"\w*, \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w an|strong="G2532"\w* \w angel|strong="G2597"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*, \w descending|strong="G2597"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w heaven|strong="G3772"\w*, \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w come|strong="G1096"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w rolled|strong="G3037"\w* back \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w stone|strong="G3037"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* door,\f + \fr 28:2 \ft Perhaps 0.5% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit “from the door” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w sat|strong="G2521"\w* \w on|strong="G1537"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w*!\f + \fr 28:2 \ft The stone was not removed to let Jesus out, but to let the witnesses in.\f*  
\v 3 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w his|strong="G2532"\w* \w appearance|strong="G2397"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w like|strong="G5613"\w* lightning \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w his|strong="G2532"\w* \w clothing|strong="G1742"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w white|strong="G3022"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w snow|strong="G5510"\w*.  
\v 4 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w guards|strong="G5083"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w shaken|strong="G4579"\w* \w for|strong="G1161"\w* \w fear|strong="G5401"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w became|strong="G1096"\w* \w like|strong="G5613"\w* \w dead|strong="G3498"\w* \w men|strong="G3588"\w*.   
\s1 The angel does his duty  
\p
\v 5 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* angel \w spoke|strong="G3004"\w* \w up|strong="G3361"\w* \w and|strong="G1161"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w women|strong="G1135"\w*:\f + \fr 28:5 \ft Comparing this account with Mark 16:5-7 we conclude that the women did not see the angel outside on the stone—he only appeared to them inside the tomb. And if a shining angel had been on the stone Magdalene would not have assumed that the body had been stolen (John 20:2). If I had been one of those guards I think I would have converted on the spot—surely some of them believed and later they gave their eyewitness account to the Christian community.\f* “\w Do|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w be|strong="G3361"\w* \w afraid|strong="G5399"\w*! \w I|strong="G1161"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w looking|strong="G2212"\w* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w crucified|strong="G4717"\w*.  
\v 6 \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w here|strong="G5602"\w*, \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w risen|strong="G1453"\w*, \w just|strong="G2531"\w* \w like|strong="G2531"\w* \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w*! \w Come|strong="G1205"\w*, \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w place|strong="G5117"\w* \w where|strong="G3699"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Lord|strong="G3588"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w lying|strong="G2749"\w*.\f + \fr 28:6 \ft Perhaps 0.5% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit “the Lord” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f*  
\v 7 \w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w go|strong="G4198"\w* \w quickly|strong="G5035"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w tell|strong="G3004"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w risen|strong="G1453"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w dead|strong="G3498"\w*; \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w get|strong="G1453"\w* \w this|strong="G3588"\w*, \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w going|strong="G4198"\w* \w before|strong="G4254"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*; \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*. \w There|strong="G1563"\w*, \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*!”\f + \fr 28:7 \ft It almost sounds like he was glad to get it off his chest. I wonder why.\f*  
\v 8 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G2532"\w* \w out|strong="G2532"\w* \w quickly|strong="G5035"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w tomb|strong="G3419"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w fear|strong="G5401"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w great|strong="G3173"\w* \w joy|strong="G5479"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w ran|strong="G5143"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* report \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w*.   
\s1 Jesus' second appearance  
\p
\v 9 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w as|strong="G1161"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w going|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* report \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3588"\w*,\f + \fr 28:9 \ft Some 12% of the Greek manuscripts omit this first clause (as in NIV, NASB, [LB], TEV, etc.). Mark 16:9 makes clear that the first appearance was to Magdalene.\f* wow, \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w met|strong="G5221"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*, “\w Rejoice|strong="G5463"\w*!” \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w approaching|strong="G4334"\w*, \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w held|strong="G2902"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w feet|strong="G4228"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w worshiped|strong="G4352"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*.  
\v 10 \w Then|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w Do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w afraid|strong="G5399"\w*! \w Go|strong="G5217"\w* report \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w my|strong="G3708"\w* brothers\f + \fr 28:10 \ft The angel said “disciples”, but Jesus said “brothers”. It may be that He was referring precisely to His half-brothers James, Jude, etc. They would not have been in the upper room with the Eleven, and so did not see Him at that time.\f* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w must|strong="G5399"\w* \w go|strong="G5217"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w there|strong="G1563"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.”   
\s1 Guards are bribed  
\p
\v 11 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w while|strong="G1161"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w going|strong="G4198"\w*, \w get|strong="G1096"\w* \w this|strong="G3588"\w*, \w some|strong="G5100"\w* \w of|strong="G5100"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w guard|strong="G2892"\w* \w went|strong="G4198"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w city|strong="G4172"\w* \w and|strong="G1161"\w* reported \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* chief priests \w all|strong="G1161"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G3588"\w* \w happened|strong="G1096"\w*.\f + \fr 28:11 \ft “Some”—so where were the rest? Those who were converted, as I suppose, would not want to be part of the cover-up.\f*  
\v 12 \w When|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w met|strong="G4863"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w elders|strong="G4245"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w consulted|strong="G4824"\w* \w together|strong="G4863"\w*, \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w gave|strong="G1325"\w* plenty \w of|strong="G2532"\w* money \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w soldiers|strong="G4757"\w*  
\v 13 \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w Say|strong="G3004"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w his|strong="G3754"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w at|strong="G3588"\w* \w night|strong="G3571"\w* \w and|strong="G2064"\w* \w stole|strong="G2813"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w while|strong="G2837"\w* \w you|strong="G3754"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w sleeping|strong="G2837"\w*.  
\v 14 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w should|strong="G3588"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w get|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w governor|strong="G2232"\w*, \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w persuade|strong="G3982"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w make|strong="G4160"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* safe.”  
\v 15 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w taking|strong="G2983"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* money \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w did|strong="G4160"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w instructed|strong="G1321"\w*. \w Their|strong="G2532"\w* tale \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w widely|strong="G1310"\w* \w spread|strong="G1310"\w* \w among|strong="G3844"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w* \w until|strong="G3360"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*.   
\ms1 The Great Commission  
\p
\v 16 \w The|strong="G1519"\w* \w eleven|strong="G1733"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w went|strong="G4198"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w Galilee|strong="G1056"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w mountain|strong="G3735"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w had|strong="G2424"\w* indicated \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*.  
\v 17 \w When|strong="G1161"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w saw|strong="G3708"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w worshiped|strong="G4352"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*; \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w some|strong="G3588"\w* \w doubted|strong="G1365"\w*.\f + \fr 28:17 \ft The Text actually says “they doubted”—it seems improbable that all of them would doubt (after all, they had seen Him at least twice already), so most translations render “some”. Although verse 16 refers specifically to the eleven, there may have been others (like His half-brothers, verse 10) along who had not seen Him yet.\f*  
\v 18 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w approaching|strong="G4334"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* asserted \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w All|strong="G3956"\w* \w authority|strong="G1849"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w heaven|strong="G3772"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w on|strong="G1909"\w* \w earth|strong="G1093"\w* \w has|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G2532"\w* \w given|strong="G1325"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w*.  
\v 19 \w As|strong="G1519"\w* \w you|strong="G1438"\w* \w go|strong="G4198"\w*,\f + \fr 28:19 \ft The familiar ‘therefore’ is found in perhaps 5% of the Greek manuscripts.\f* \w make|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3100"\w* \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* ethnic \w nations|strong="G1484"\w*: baptizing \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w*;\f + \fr 28:19 \ft Our Lord defines the Trinity here. According to Greek grammar the use of ‘and’ plus the definite article with items in a series makes clear that the items are distinct entities. So “the Father” is different from “the Son” is different from “the Holy Spirit”. So we have three persons. But He also said, “in \+nd the\+nd* name”, singular, not ‘names’. So we have only one name. God is one ‘name’ or essence subsisting in three persons.\f*  
\v 20 \w teaching|strong="G1321"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w obey|strong="G5083"\w* \w everything|strong="G3956"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w commanded|strong="G1781"\w* \nd \+w you|strong="G5210"\+w*\nd*;\f + \fr 28:20 \ft The ‘you’ here refers to the eleven (see verse 16), so they were to pass down all the commands that Jesus had given them. To be a disciple of Jesus you have to do everything that Jesus had commanded the eleven to do—this includes healing and casting out demons, as well as preaching the Gospel.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w take|strong="G2532"\w* note, \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*, \w until|strong="G2193"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w end|strong="G4930"\w* \w of|strong="G2250"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* age!”\f + \fr 28:20 \ft Since the age has not ended, Jesus is still with us. Praise God!\f*  
\p Amen.   